  "topic_name": "Motion",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Motion is the change in position of an object with respect to its surroundings over time. An object at rest does not change its position. Motion can be of different types: rectilinear (straight line), circular, rotational, and oscillatory. Speed is the distance covered per unit time, measured in metres per second (m/s). Velocity is speed in a particular direction. Uniform motion means equal distances are covered in equal time intervals, while non-uniform motion means unequal distances in equal time intervals. Distance-time graphs help visualize motion - a straight line indicates uniform motion.",
    "rules": [
      "Rest: no change in position with respect to surroundings.",
      "Motion: change in position with respect to surroundings.",
      "Speed = Distance / Time.",
      "SI unit of speed: metre per second (m/s).",
      "Uniform motion: equal distances in equal time intervals.",
      "Non-uniform motion: unequal distances in equal time intervals.",
      "Distance-time graph for uniform motion is a straight line."
    ]
  },
